description: From Ancient Greek δίς (dís, “twice, doubly”) + πρωτο- (prōto-) (combination form of πρῶτος (prôtos, “first”), superlative of πρό (pró, “before”)) + ὀδούς (odoús, “tooth”) or ὀδών (odṓn) (Ionic) — hence “two front teeth.”

entries.meaning: Any individual of the extinct marsupial genus Diprotodon, similar to a wombat in appearance but the size of a small elephant.
examples: No fewer than eighty diprotodons are represented by the bones already unearthed,  […]
